Fractionation of âˆ‚13C to Review Energetic Potentials in a Serpentinized Environment

Patrick Thieringer

Overview of Serpenitnized Environment

From last week, we know that within the deeper zones of a serpentinized system the carbon availability becomes limiting and the residual DIC \(\delta^{13}C\) becomes highly enriched. Atmospheric \(CO_2\) equiibrates with the surface fluid and begins to evolve into â€œType Iâ€ groundwaters where KIEâ€™s of hydroxylation begin the inital depletion of DIC, then followed by mixing with â€œType IIâ€ waters where carbonate precipitation that inherits the depleted \(\delta^{13}C\) values results in a successively limited carbon source availbility but incredibly enirched \(\delta^{13}C\) source for methanogens to use.

knitr::include_graphics("Zwicker 2018.png")

Weâ€™re interested to see if we can tease out the energetics for methanogenesis within this system to see if it is favorable for methanogens in the subsurface serpentinized enrionment. Weâ€™ll use reported and estimated isotopic values to calculate fractionation values and then relate that to a model that can potentially estimate \(âˆ†G\). Similarly, we can help evaluate the \(\delta^{13}C\) values from a residual DIC pool that may be necessary to microbially produce enriched \(\delta ^{13}CH_4\) values.

Fractionation of CO2 and CH4

Reported Values

The paper we discussed reports \(\delta^{13}C_{CH_4}\) from a previous study (Etiope et al.Â 2011). Weâ€™re going to use a fixed value in order to interpret the range of \(\delta^{13}C_{CO_2}\) that may be availalable.

delta_CH4 <- -0.012

Estimating \(\delta^{13}C\) of CO2

The same paper by Etiope et al. (2011) has reported \(\delta^{13}C_{CO_2}\) values from gas generated from one of the seeps. However, our study reported \(\delta^{13}C_{lipid}\) to inference the residual DIC available to methanogens may be extremely enriched. Here weâ€™ll use a sequence of values to see what values may be availbale and if they all fit into predicting energetic potentials. Weâ€™re assuming the DIC values we are estimating are in the form of dissovled \(CO_2\) for use by methanogens in our system.

delta_CO2_reported <- seq(-0.018, -0.015, by = 0.001)
delta_CO2_est <- seq(-0.014, 0.012, by = 0.001) #Predicting values higher than the reported based off of the lipid-isotope values from Zwicker et al. (2018)

Calculating the Fractionation Values for our methanogens

\[ \alpha_{{CO_2}-{CH_4}} = \frac{\delta_{CO_2} + 1}{\delta_{CH_4} + 1} \] Please solve for this to include the reported and estimated \(\delta^{13}C_{CO_2}\) values:

#Alpha values for reported and estimated conditions
alpha_CO2_CH4_reported <- tibble( 
  alpha_CO2_CH4 = (delta_CO2_reported + 1) / (delta_CH4 +1),
  Scenario = "Reported")
alpha_CO2_CH4_est <- tibble(
  alpha_CO2_CH4 = (delta_CO2_est + 1) / (delta_CH4 +1),
  Scenario = "Estimated")

#Combine both for downstream use
alpha_CO2_CH4_df <- rbind(alpha_CO2_CH4_est, alpha_CO2_CH4_reported)

The \(\alpha - âˆ†G\) relationship

Solving for \(âˆ†G\)

Penning et al. (2005) reported the use of a \(\alpha-âˆ†G\) relationship that could be used to predict potential \(âˆ†G\) values in environmental samples where other environmental parameters are difficult to determine.

knitr::include_graphics("Penning 2005.png")

Since we know our \(\alpha_{{CO_2}-{CH_4}}\), we can then use our known values to â€œguessâ€ our \(âˆ†G\) energetic potnetials for methanogens in this system. Remember, this is a first pass to just assess what might be feasible, and is not a direct correlation.

\[ \alpha_{{CO_2}-{CH_4}} = y_o + A\ \exp[-(âˆ†G - x_c)^2 / 2w^2] \\\ \\ y_o = 1 \\ A = 0.0919 \\ x_c = 11.8376\\ w = 78.0067 \]

Solve for \(âˆ†G\): \[ âˆ†G = \sqrt{(-2w^2 \cdot \ln(\frac{\alpha_{CO_2-CH_4} - y_o}{A}))} + x_c \]

Predicitng \(âˆ†G\)

Letâ€™s now use our new equation and \(\alpha_{{CO_2}-{CH_4}}\) values to see if we can predict the energetic favorability of methanogenesis.

Plot the \(\alpha - âˆ†G\) relationship and assess the estimated energetic availbility

alpha_CO2_CH4_df <- mutate(alpha_CO2_CH4_df,
  y_o = 1,
  A = 0.0919,
  x_c = 11.8376,
  w = 78.0067,
  delta_G = (sqrt((-2 * w^2) * log((alpha_CO2_CH4 - y_o) / A)) + x_c) * -1 #Need to account for âˆ†G which is negative when plotting the curve
)

The Regression Line calculated from Penning et al. (2015) and the 95% confidence intervals for reference in plots

reg_line_df <- tibble(
  y_o = 1,
  A = 0.0919,
  x_c = 11.8376,
  w = 78.0067,
  reg_line_values = seq(1.001, 1.09, by = 0.001),
  reg_line_equation = (sqrt((-2 * w^2) * log((reg_line_values - y_o) / A)) + x_c) * -1
)
reg_line_df2 <- tibble(
  y_o = 1,
  A = 0.1023,
  x_c = 35.3598,
  w = 92.1194,
  reg_line_values = seq(1.001, 1.09, by = 0.001),
  reg_line_equation = (sqrt((-2 * w^2) * log((reg_line_values - y_o) / A)) + x_c) * -1
)
reg_line_df3 <- tibble(
  y_o = 1,
  A = 0.0815,
  x_c = -11.6846,
  w = 63.894,
  reg_line_values = seq(1.001, 1.09, by = 0.001),
  reg_line_equation = (sqrt((-2 * w^2) * log((reg_line_values - y_o) / A)) + x_c) * -1
)

Evaluating the \(\alpha - âˆ†G\) relationship based on modeled values

Zwicker et al. (2019) did \(âˆ†G_{methanogenesis}\) calculations through model experiments based off of the amount of dissolved gasses (\(CH_4\) and \(H_2\)). Letâ€™s assume that the methanogens of interest are operating in the lower extremes of the serpentinized system of around 30 degrees C and 0.1 fraction of gasses are dissolved in the hyperalkaline fluids.

What can we gu-estimate our \(âˆ†G_{methanogenesis}\) to be? Letâ€™s now plot this against our previously estimated values:
